<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Male. Head</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov., male (ECOSCE 4925): A head, frontal, male B dorsal view C lateral view. Female (ECOSCE 24472): D head, frontal view E dorsal view F lateral view. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402758" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">4A, C</figureCitation>
). Black, covered with white pollinosity, oral tips, ocellar triangle, and a large triangular macula on the front, brown pilose, pile on front black, on gena and face white pilose, on ocellar triangle black pilose, on the occiput white except the dorsal pile, which are black, frontal triangle golden metallic. Antennae brown, orange-red ventrally, oval, longer than wide pedicel and the lower basal corner of basoflagellomere, long, ratio 1.0:1.2:3.0, arista orange, dark brown toward the tip. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Thorax</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov., male (ECOSCE 4925): A head, frontal, male B dorsal view C lateral view. Female (ECOSCE 24472): D head, frontal view E dorsal view F lateral view. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402758" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">4C</figureCitation>
). Black, the scutum opaque, shining, with iridescent to opaque reflections, with two median brownish pollinose vittae on anterior half. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Wing</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov., male (ECOSCE 4925): A head, frontal, male B dorsal view C lateral view. Female (ECOSCE 24472): D head, frontal view E dorsal view F lateral view. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402758" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">4C</figureCitation>
). Slightly smoky, the stigma brown, membrane microtrichose, except for extensive bare areas on basal half (cells, c, sc, r1, dm and bm); tegula black pilose, basicosta yellow pilose, alula bare, calypter whitish, border whitish, fringe yellow, plumula yellow, halter yellow, knob white. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Legs</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov., male (ECOSCE 4925): A head, frontal, male B dorsal view C lateral view. Female (ECOSCE 24472): D head, frontal view E dorsal view F lateral view. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402758" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">4C</figureCitation>
). Yellow, pro- and mesofemur yellow; metafemur orange on basal 1/5 and apical 3/5; pro- and mesotibia orange with a brown macula on posterior medial edge, metatibia extensively brown, only orange brownish on basal 2/3; metacoxa black pilose; pro, meso- and metabasitarsomere I-II yellow, the pile yellow, black on the metatibia and above on the tarsi. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Abdomen</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov., male (ECOSCE 4925): A head, frontal, male B dorsal view C lateral view. Female (ECOSCE 24472): D head, frontal view E dorsal view F lateral view. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402758" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">4B</figureCitation>
). Elongate, black, first tergum shining black, second tergum with a pair of broad maculae, reaching apical 1/2, third tergum with a short rounded basomedial fascia. Pile orange on the sides basally, black down the middle and on the apical terga, as well as in the maculae. Male genitalia as Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov., male genitalia: A whole genitalia including epandrium, cercus, and surstylus, lateral view B epandrium, dorsal view C hypandrium, ventral view. Scale bar: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402759" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">5</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Female.</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov., male (ECOSCE 4925): A head, frontal, male B dorsal view C lateral view. Female (ECOSCE 24472): D head, frontal view E dorsal view F lateral view. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402758" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">4D-F</figureCitation>
). Similar to male except for normal sexual dimorphism. Abdominal maculae on tergum third comparatively shorter than in the male and restricted to the center of the tergum, no reaching the lateral margin, maculae on fourth and fifth tergum absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Length</emphasis>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">N</emphasis>
= 5). Body 12.5-12.8 mm; wing 11.4-11.7 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="huitepecensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="huitepecensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">huitepecensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(noun in the genitive case) is derived from the Mixtec (native language spoken in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="México">Mexico</normalizedToken>
) word &quot; 
<taxonomicName genus="Huitztli" lsidName="Huitztli" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Huitztli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; which means: thorns, &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tépeltque">Tepeltque</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
&quot; means: hill, combined with the Latin suffix - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">ensis</emphasis>
, meaning from a place. The name is given in reference to the Huitepec Ecological Reserve where the species was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montoya" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Argentinomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Argentinomyia huitepecensis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huitepecensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Argentinomyia huitepecensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">N</emphasis>
= 7) is the northernmost distributed species of the larger 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lynch Arribalzaga" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Argentinomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Argentinomyia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Argentinomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, recorded on the western slope of the Chiapas-Guatemalan Highlands, and inhabiting cloud forest at an elevation between 1800 to 2400 m. a.s.l. The species is exclusively known from the province of Chiapas Highlands (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Biogeographical distribution of Argentinomyia huitepecensis sp. nov. (green), A. talamanca sp. nov. (red) and A. puntarenas sp. nov. (blue)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.929.37666.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402770" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
